---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const concepts = await getCollection("concepts");
const contributors = (await getCollection("contributors")).sort((a, b) =>
  a.data.name.localeCompare(b.data.name),
);

// Qualitative credit only: what each person worked on, never counts or
// ranks. See CLAUDE.md section 25.
const people = contributors.map((contributor) => ({
  ...contributor,
  initials: contributor.data.name
    .split(/\s+/)
    .slice(0, 2)
    .map((part) => part[0])
    .join(""),
  wrote: concepts
    .filter((concept) => concept.data.authors.includes(contributor.id))
    .sort((a, b) => a.data.title.localeCompare(b.data.title)),
  reviewed: concepts
    .filter((concept) => concept.data.reviewers.includes(contributor.id))
    .sort((a, b) => a.data.title.localeCompare(b.data.title)),
}));

const loop = [
  "Learn",
  "Explain",
  "Discuss",
  "Review",
  "Refine",
  "Publish",
  "Connect",
  "Learn deeper",
];

// Principles are inlined in the markup below: the first one carries an
// external link, so plain strings stopped being enough.
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About | OpenDS"
  description="OpenDS is a small community that learns Data Science and AI by teaching it: writing explanations, peer-reviewing them, and connecting them into a knowledge graph."
>
  <main class="gutter container-reading pt-10 pb-14">
    <h1
      class="max-w-[24ch] font-serif text-[clamp(2rem,4vw,3rem)] leading-[1.15] font-medium tracking-tight"
    >
      About OpenDS
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-5 font-serif text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
      AI has made it possible to learn about everything at once, and we did.
      Answers arrive in seconds, summaries of whole fields fit on one screen,
      and it all feels understood until the moment you actually need it. Then
      you try to explain the idea, or defend it in a review, or build something
      on top of it, and discover the understanding was never really yours.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-4 font-serif text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
      OpenDS is a small community of people relearning Data Science and AI by
      teaching it to each other. When one of us finally understands something
      properly, we write it down the way we wish someone had explained it to us,
      and then the others pull the draft apart until it holds. Nothing gets
      published until someone who did not write it has worked through every
      claim. Article by article, the results link into a{" "}
      <a href="/map" class="text-accent hover:underline">knowledge map</a>{" "}
      that a future learner might find useful.
    </p>

    <section aria-labelledby="how-it-works" class="mt-14">
      <h2
        id="how-it-works"
        class="font-sans text-sm font-semibold tracking-wide text-ink-muted uppercase"
      >
        How it works
      </h2>
      <p
        class="mt-4 flex max-w-full flex-wrap items-baseline gap-x-2 gap-y-1 font-mono text-[0.8125rem] tracking-wide text-ink-muted"
      >
        {
          loop.map((step, i) => (
            <Fragment>
              <span>{step}</span>
              {i < loop.length - 1 && (
                <span aria-hidden="true" class="text-ink-faint">
                  →
                </span>
              )}
            </Fragment>
          ))
        }
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-6">
        <li class="border-t border-hairline py-5">
          <h3 class="font-sans text-base font-semibold tracking-tight">
            Learn by teaching
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-1.5 font-serif leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
            Explaining a concept in writing is the fastest way to discover you
            only half understood it. The idea is old and has a name, the{" "}
            <a
              href="https://fs.blog/feynman-technique/"
              class="text-accent hover:underline"
            >
              Feynman Technique
            </a>: explain the concept in plain language, watch where your
            explanation breaks down, and go back to study until it does not.
            Every author here comes out the other side knowing the topic better
            than when they started.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="border-t border-hairline py-5">
          <h3 class="font-sans text-base font-semibold tracking-tight">
            Peer review by default
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-1.5 font-serif leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
            Before anything is published, a reviewer works through the draft,
            questions the claims, and pushes on the intuition until it actually
            convinces. Review here is how two people learn at once, not a gate
            to keep anyone out.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="border-t border-hairline py-5">
          <h3 class="font-sans text-base font-semibold tracking-tight">
            Curated over crowded
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-1.5 font-serif leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
            We would rather publish twenty excellent, connected pages than two
            hundred shallow ones, so nothing gets rushed out the door. Taking
            months over an article is fine. Publishing something misleading is
            not.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="border-t border-b border-hairline py-5">
          <h3 class="font-sans text-base font-semibold tracking-tight">
            Connected knowledge
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-1.5 font-serif leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
            Every concept states what you should learn before it and what it
            opens up next, and the map is drawn directly from those
            declarations. It never drifts out of date, because it cannot.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="the-people" class="mt-14">
      <h2
        id="the-people"
        class="font-sans text-sm font-semibold tracking-wide text-ink-muted uppercase"
      >
        The people
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-4 font-serif leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
        OpenDS began as a group of friends who did not want to stop learning
        together after graduation. Some of us write, some review, some build the
        widgets and animations that make an explanation finally click. Credit
        here simply says who worked on what. There are no counts and no
        leaderboards, because none of those ever made anyone a better teacher.
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-6 grid gap-5 sm:grid-cols-2">
        {
          people.map((person) => (
            <li class="rounded border border-hairline p-5">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-4">
                {person.data.avatar ? (
                  <img
                    src={person.data.avatar}
                    alt=""
                    class="h-14 w-14 shrink-0 rounded-full border border-hairline object-cover"
                  />
                ) : (
                  <span
                    aria-hidden="true"
                    class="flex h-14 w-14 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full border border-hairline bg-surface font-sans text-lg font-semibold text-ink-muted"
                  >
                    {person.initials}
                  </span>
                )}
                <div class="min-w-0">
                  <h3 class="font-sans text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
                    {person.data.name}
                  </h3>
                  {person.data.role && (
                    <p class="font-sans text-sm text-ink-muted">
                      {person.data.role}
                    </p>
                  )}
                </div>
              </div>

              {person.data.bio && (
                <p class="mt-4 font-serif text-[0.9375rem] leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
                  {person.data.bio}
                </p>
              )}

              {person.data.interests.length > 0 && (
                <p class="mt-3 font-sans text-[0.8125rem] text-ink-faint">
                  Into {person.data.interests.join(", ")}
                </p>
              )}

              {(person.wrote.length > 0 || person.reviewed.length > 0) && (
                <div class="mt-4 space-y-1 border-t border-hairline pt-3 font-sans text-sm text-ink-muted">
                  {person.wrote.length > 0 && (
                    <p>
                      Wrote{" "}
                      {person.wrote.map((concept, i) => (
                        <Fragment>
                          <a
                            href={`/concepts/${concept.data.slug}`}
                            class="text-ink underline decoration-hairline underline-offset-4 hover:text-accent"
                          >
                            {concept.data.title}
                          </a>
                          {i < person.wrote.length - 1 && ", "}
                        </Fragment>
                      ))}
                    </p>
                  )}
                  {person.reviewed.length > 0 && (
                    <p>
                      Reviewed{" "}
                      {person.reviewed.map((concept, i) => (
                        <Fragment>
                          <a
                            href={`/concepts/${concept.data.slug}`}
                            class="text-ink underline decoration-hairline underline-offset-4 hover:text-accent"
                          >
                            {concept.data.title}
                          </a>
                          {i < person.reviewed.length - 1 && ", "}
                        </Fragment>
                      ))}
                    </p>
                  )}
                </div>
              )}

              {(person.data.github ||
                person.data.linkedin ||
                person.data.website) && (
                <p class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-x-4 font-sans text-sm text-ink-muted">
                  {person.data.github && (
                    <a
                      href={`https://github.com/${person.data.github}`}
                      class="hover:text-accent"
                    >
                      GitHub
                    </a>
                  )}
                  {person.data.linkedin && (
                    <a href={person.data.linkedin} class="hover:text-accent">
                      LinkedIn
                    </a>
                  )}
                  {person.data.website && (
                    <a href={person.data.website} class="hover:text-accent">
                      Website
                    </a>
                  )}
                </p>
              )}
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="join-in" class="mt-14" id="join-in">
      <h2
        class="font-sans text-sm font-semibold tracking-wide text-ink-muted uppercase"
      >
        Join in
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-4 font-serif leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
        <p>
          You do not need to be a software engineer to write for OpenDS. If you
          are comfortable with git, you write your article in MDX and open a
          pull request like any other change. If you are not, you draft in
          whatever writing tool you like and a maintainer ports it over for you.
          Both paths end in the same friendly peer review, and both count
          exactly the same.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          If you are not sure what to write, the{" "}
          <a href="/map" class="text-accent hover:underline">map</a>{" "}
          is full of planned concepts waiting for an author to claim them. The full
          guide lives in the repository at{" "}
          <code class="font-mono text-[0.85em] tracking-tight text-ink"
            >docs/CONTRIBUTING.md</code
          >, alongside the style and review guides.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
